etm_info:
Most likely substantivized[1] from Proto-Balto-Slavic *bÃ¡lË€tas (â€œfaint, whiteâ€). Cognate with Lithuanian bÃ¡ltas (â€œwhiteâ€), balÃ  (â€œswampâ€), Latvian balts (â€œwhiteâ€), and the second part of Old Prussian placename Namuyn-balt.
The semantic connection between "white" and "swamp, mud" is not obvious, but has been attested in many languages. Beside the mentioned Lithuanian, also in e.g., Old Polish biel (â€œmud, swampâ€) (< *bÄ›lÑŒ, from *bÄ›lÑŠ (â€œwhiteâ€)). This is probably due to the widespread presence of the marsh grass called cottongrass (genus Eriophorum), whose the white fluffy seed heads are white, or the color of the dried clay taking light hue, depending on soil.
Though formally and semantically derivable from Proto-Indo-European *bÊ°elH- (â€œwhiteâ€), with cognates such as Albanian baltÃ« (â€œmudâ€), Romanian baltÄƒ (â€œmud, swampâ€) and Greek Î²Î¬Î»Ï„Î¿Ï‚ (vÃ¡ltos, â€œswampâ€), it is often considered an Illyrian substratum word (or from another, unidentified substrate language; cf. Proto-Slavic *bala (â€œmarshâ€)) due to the fact that most of the cognates are restricted to the Balkan peninsula, or its surroundings. However, these can also be borrowings from early Slavic; indirect evidence shows that the Slavic liquid metathesis and pleophony happened well after the spread of Slavic to the Balkans and the word must have been pronounced as *balta or *bolto as recently as the late 8th century.

ESSJa treats it as as a single headword, Derksen as two (separating meanings "harrow" and "guarded entrance, barrier"), and SÅ‚awski as three ("harrow", "defended/defending object" and "membrane").

Cognates include Latin forÅ (â€œto bore, pierceâ€), Old Norse bora (â€œto bore, drillâ€) and Ancient Greek Ï†Î¬ÏÏ‰ (phÃ¡rÅ), Ï†Î¬ÏÎ¿Ï‚ (phÃ¡ros). From the same root also Common Slavic *bÑŒrdo (â€œweaving comb, reedâ€), *boriti sÄ™ (â€œto fightâ€), and *borzda (â€œfurrowâ€).
SÅ‚awski derives the set of meanings "protection, guard, defense; object of protecting, defending, gate, dam, barrier, fortification" as an action noun of the verb *borniti (â€œto guard, protect, defendâ€). Derksen legitimizes separate treatment due to the semantic difficulties of connecting Common Slavic *borti (â€œto fight, conquerâ€) as well as other Indo-European cognates (Latin feriÅ (â€œto hit, strikeâ€), Old Norse berja (â€œto beat, hitâ€)) with the root *bÊ°erhâ‚ƒ- (â€œto hit with a sharp instrumentâ€).

There may be two Indo-European roots involved, *mey- (â€œto tie, strengthenâ€) and *mehhâ‚- (â€œsoft, mildâ€).
Root-cognates (with different suffixes) include, with the former: Ancient Greek Î¼Î¯Ï„Î¿Ï‚ (mÃ­tos, â€œwarp threadâ€), Proto-Indo-Iranian *mitrÃ¡s (literally â€œ(that which) causes bindingâ€) (Old Persian ğ·ğ°ğ¼ (mi-Î¸-r), and Sanskrit à¤®à¤¿à¤¤à¥à¤° (mitra)); with the latter:  Proto-Slavic *milÑŠ (â€œnice, gentle, mildâ€), Latin mÄ«tis (â€œmild, calm, peacefulâ€).[1]
The dual meaning of "peace" and "world" is unique to Slavic, and scholarly opinion is divided on whether this is a purely semantic development (via a meaning of "pact, friendship" to "community, society" to "ecumene, inhabited world") or alternatively an early conflation of two words, with the meaning "world" derived only from the root meaning "to bind", and the meaning "peace" derived from the root meaning "gentle, mild".[2]

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *auÅ¡(t)ra- (â€œdawn, morningâ€), from Proto-Indo-European *hâ‚‚ews-ro- (â€œof the dawn or morning, matutinal; easternâ€), from *hâ‚‚ews- (â€œdawn; eastâ€). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian auÅ¡rÃ , dial. auÅ¡trÃ  (â€œdawnâ€), Latvian Ã ustra, aÅ©stra (â€œdawnâ€). Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek Î±á½”Ïá¾± (aÃºrÄ, â€œ(esp. cool) breeze, fresh air of the morningâ€), Latin auster (â€œsouth windâ€), Proto-Germanic *austrÄ… (â€œeastâ€), Proto-Germanic *AustrÇ­ (â€œEaster, springtime; name of a goddessâ€) (presumably from the goddess of the dawn, lust, fertility and spring, associated with the beginning of the year).
A variant *jutro appears in West Slavic, Slovenian and Serbo-Croatian, and is also attested in Old Church Slavonic, but considered secondary; there are further Slavic lexemes that display an alternation *ju- in West and South Slavic vs. *u- in East Slavic. Variants with *(j)ustr- point to *ustr- < *usr-,[1] the loss of -s- being either due to dissimilation[2] or perhaps due to the law of open syllables, if the -s- was variably assigned to the end of the first syllable. According to Kortlandt, the acute on the root implies a zero-grade variant (which would have parallels in Sanskrit à¤‰à¤¸à¥à¤° (usrÃ¡-, â€œreddish, ruddy, bright, matutinalâ€), à¤‰à¤¸à¥à¤°à¤¾ (usrÄÌ-, â€œdawn, morningâ€)), which, however, is not attested.[3] The intrusive -t- is regular in Proto-Slavic, compare *ostrÑŠ, *strumy.

etm_info:

The central Indo-European word for "fish" *dÊ°ÇµÊ°u- (â€œfishâ€) (yielding Ancient Greek á¼°Ï‡Î¸ÏÏ‚ (ikhthÃºs), Lithuanian Å¾uvÃ¬s, Old Armenian Õ±Õ¸Ö‚Õ¯Õ¶ (jukn)) would have given Proto-Slavic v-stem **zy (genitive **zÑŠve, accusative **zÑŠvÑŒ), and was, as the theory goes, avoided by fishermen due to taboo, or because it would have sounded too similar to the verb *zÑŠvati (â€œto callâ€).
Some of the proposed etymologies include:

Toporov: From Early Proto-Slavic *rÅ³Ì„bÄ, which is then comparable to *rÄ™bÑŠ (â€œspeckled, motley, variegatedâ€), with fish scales being the semantic connection. For a similar development compare *pÑŒstry (â€œsalmonid fishâ€), originally "the colorful/variegated one" < *pÑŒstrÑŠ (â€œvariegatedâ€).
Loewenthal: From earlier *rÅ³Ì„bÄ, but instead from Proto-Indo-European *wremb- (â€œto twist aroundâ€), akin to Proto-Germanic *wrimpanÄ… (â€œto winceâ€), Ancient Greek á¿¥Î­Î¼Î²Ï‰ (rhÃ©mbÅ, â€œto roam, to turn in circlesâ€). Doubted by Vasmer.
Vaillant: Perhaps originally a collection/action noun from *ryti (â€œto dig, to snoutâ€) +â€ *-ba, initially referring to the process â€œfishingâ€ and later (by abstraction) to the yield â€œfishâ€.
Mladenov: Akin to Proto-Slavic *ruxÑŠ (â€œmovement, deformationâ€), *ryxlÑŠ (â€œswift, quickâ€), from Proto-Indo-European *hâ‚ƒrew- (â€œto hurryâ€).
Jakobson, Schmalstieg, Snoj: From Proto-Balto-Slavic *jÅ«Ë€r- (â€œwater, swamp, pondâ€), whence Lithuanian jÅ«Ìra (â€œseaâ€), Latvian jÅ«ra (â€œseaâ€) and perhaps akin to Proto-Slavic *juriti (â€œto charge, to plungeâ€), *jurÑŠkÑŠ (â€œwhisk, agileâ€), with a rare metathesis *Å«r- > *rÅ«- + the suffix *-ba for forming abstract nouns.
Early scholars (Uhlenbeck, Berneker, Mikkola, Walde-Hofmann) had tentatively compared the Slavic word with Old High German rÅ«ppa (â€œcaterpillarâ€) or Latin rubÄ“ta (â€œbramble toadâ€), which nowadays are commonly viewed as unrelated.

From Proto-Balto-Slavic *grÄÌË€bÄ«Ë€tei.

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°rob-Ã©ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°reb-; meanings "to rake" in daughter languages from confusion with the root *gÊ°rebÊ°- (see Proto-Slavic *gretÃ¬ (â€œto dig, to rake, to scrapeâ€)). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian grÃ³bti (â€œto seizeâ€), Latvian grÃ¢bt (â€œto seizeâ€). Indo-European cognates include Old Norse grÃ¡pa (â€œto seizeâ€). The same confusion appears to have happened elsewhere; compare Sanskrit à¤—à¥ƒà¤¹à¥à¤£à¤¾à¤¤à¤¿ (gá¹›há¹‡ÄÌti), à¤—à¥ƒà¤­à¥à¤£à¤¾à¤¤à¤¿ (gá¹›bhá¹‡ÄÌti, â€œto seize, to hold, to takeâ€). Avestan: grab- â€˜to grab, seize, takeâ€™, Old Persian: grab- â€˜to seize (as possesion), Persian Ú¯Ø±ÙØªÙ†â€ (gereftan), Ù¾Ø°ÛŒØ±ÙØªÙ†â€ (paziroftan).[1] English grab vs. Gothic ğŒ²ğ‚ğŒ°ğŒ±ğŒ°ğŒ½ (graban, â€œto digâ€), all of which come from *gÊ°rebÊ°-. Derksen does not derive this verb from *gÊ°rebÊ°- due to Winter's law, which is required to produce the acute *-a- of the Slavic root but would not operate in *gÊ°rebÊ°-.
Per Vasmer, Chernykh and Trubachev, this verb in fact derives from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°rob-Ã©ye-ti, from *gÊ°reb-; see also Proto-Slavic *gretÃ¬. Chernykh describes it as the causative of *gretÃ¬.
Per Rix (LIV), probably from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°robhâ‚‚-Ã©ye-ti, from *gÊ°rebhâ‚‚-, which allows for Winter's law and also accounts for the Sanskrit -(b)h- (but still doesn't account for the Germanic forms, which are supposed to derive from a different root *gÊ°rebÊ°-).

etm_info:
Ultimately from Latin Caesar, the name of Julius Caesar, whose name became part of the Roman emperor's title. The name was very early borrowed into Germanic as *kaisaraz, whence it was borrowed into Slavic from an unknown source.
The most commonly regarded etymon cited in the literature is Gothic ğŒºğŒ°ğŒ¹ğƒğŒ°ğ‚ (kaisar), though such assignment is problematic. Old High German and Old Saxon forms with the suffix -ur are less plausible etymons. Formal mismatches with Gothic form include:

Germanic short */a/ regularly yields */o/ in Common Slavic, and the reconstructions for the vowel suffix point to a short */a/. The regular suffix from the Gothic form would have been **-or.
Even if we are dealing with analogical leveling to the productive agentive suffix *-ÄÅ™ÑŒ, this still doesn't fully explain the short vowel. The Slovene form points to a short suffixal vowel, since the accent retracted from short final vowels.
If the short suffixal */-a-/ represents a late borrowing, after the Common Slavic rephonemicization of qualitative oppositions into quantitative ones, then this would exclude Gothic as the donor languages because the Goths lost their dominance in the Pontic region around the fifth century, well before such a process took place.
the C sound has been palatalized.

etm_info:
1. Sometimes explained as a deverbative of *buÄati (â€œto make noise, roarâ€) and reconstructed as *bÑŠÄela. A bee is, therefore, the one that makes noise.
2. Alternatively from North-West Proto-Indo-European *bÊ°i-kÊ·e- (â€œbee, stinging insectâ€), an extension of root *bÊ°i- (â€œto hit, strikeâ€) - compare *biti (â€œto beat, hitâ€).
The Psalterium Sinaiticum contains the only Old Church Slavonic instance of Ğ±ÑŒÑ‡ĞµĞ»Ğ° (bÄ­Äela) but since the form Ğ±ÑŠÑ‡ĞµĞ»Ğ° (bÅ­Äela) is just as rare, it is impossible to precisely reconstruct the late Proto-Slavic form of this word on the basis of Old Church Slavonic. Since this Proto-Slavic word was an oxytone, none of the descendant languages retain a reflex of the medial weak jer.
Baltic cognates (Latvian bite, Lithuanian bÃ¬tÄ—, Old Prussian bitte) would in that case render the Proto-Balto-Slavic forms as *bikelÄ“ and *bitÄ“.
3. The root of the abovementioned Proto-Balto-Slavic forms may in turn be a cognate of the roots in Old Irish bech (Irish beach), Old High German bÄ«a, Old English bÄ“o (English bee), Dutch bij, dialectal German Beie (German Biene), Old Norse bÃ½ (Danish bi). If so, the ultimate source is Proto-Indo-European *bÊ°ey-.

etm_info:
There are multiple theories:

Borrowed either from Old High German kenning (â€œsymbol, signâ€) or from a different Germanic source (compare Gothic ğŒºğŒ¿ğŒ½ğŒ½ğŒ°ğŒ½ (kunnan, â€œto knowâ€) and Old Norse kunna (â€œto knowâ€)).
From Akkadian kunukkum (â€œseal-cylinderâ€) or kanÄ«kum (â€œsealed object: document, sack bulla, etc.â€), via Old Armenian Õ¯Õ¶Õ«Ö„ (knikÊ¿, â€œsealâ€).
Ultimate Chinese origin, from å· (Middle Chinese kÉ£iuá´‡nX, kÉ£iuá´‡nH < Old Chinese *krorÊ” (â€œto roll upâ€), *kror-s (â€œscrollâ€)), as paper was invented in China around the 1st century AD. However, this seems less likely due to the likely temporal precedence of Proto-Slavic over Early Middle Chinese and the large spatial separation of the donor and recipient languages.
The second and third theories require transmission by a Turkic or an Iranian language, but nothing is attested in them. Although sometimes cited, Chuvash ĞºÓ—Ğ½ĞµĞºĞµ (kÄ•nekÌ¬e) and Ossetian Ñ‡Ğ¸Ğ½Ñ‹Ğ³ (á¸±inyg), ĞºĞ¸ÑƒĞ½ÑƒĞ³Ó• (kiwnugÃ¦) are both considered early Slavic loans. However, Hungarian kÃ¶nyv (â€œbookâ€) and Erzya ĞºĞ¾Ğ½Ñ‘Ğ² (konjov, â€œpaperâ€), which are unlikely to derive from Slavic, testify to the early presence of this word in the Volga region.

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *auÅ¡(t)ra- (â€œdawn, morningâ€), from Proto-Indo-European *hâ‚‚ews-ro- (â€œof the dawn or morning, matutinal; easternâ€), from *hâ‚‚ews- (â€œdawn; eastâ€). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian auÅ¡rÃ , dial. auÅ¡trÃ  (â€œdawnâ€), Latvian Ã ustra, aÅ©stra (â€œdawnâ€). Indo-European cognates include Ancient Greek Î±á½”Ïá¾± (aÃºrÄ, â€œ(esp. cool) breeze, fresh air of the morningâ€), Latin auster (â€œsouth windâ€), Proto-Germanic *austrÄ… (â€œeastâ€), Proto-Germanic *AustrÇ­ (â€œEaster, springtime; name of a goddessâ€) (presumably from the goddess of the dawn, lust, fertility and spring, associated with the beginning of the year).
A variant *jutro appears in West Slavic, Slovenian and Serbo-Croatian, and is also attested in Old Church Slavonic, but considered secondary; there are further Slavic lexemes that display an alternation *ju- in West and South Slavic vs. *u- in East Slavic. Variants with *(j)ustr- point to *ustr- < *usr-,[1] the loss of -s- being either due to dissimilation[2] or perhaps due to the law of open syllables, if the -s- was variably assigned to the end of the first syllable. According to Kortlandt, the acute on the root implies a zero-grade variant (which would have parallels in Sanskrit à¤‰à¤¸à¥à¤° (usrÃ¡-, â€œreddish, ruddy, bright, matutinalâ€), à¤‰à¤¸à¥à¤°à¤¾ (usrÄÌ-, â€œdawn, morningâ€)), which, however, is not attested.[3] The intrusive -t- is regular in Proto-Slavic, compare *ostrÑŠ, *strumy.

Etymology uncertain. Skok gives two hypotheses:

From a northern Turkic language, in the form ubyr or ubyrly (â€œwitchâ€). Compare Tatar ÑƒĞ±Ñ‹Ñ€ (ubÄ±r, â€œvampiric witchâ€), Chuvash Ğ²ÑƒĞ¿Ó‘Ñ€ (vupÌ¬Äƒr, â€œvampireâ€), Turkish obur (â€œgluttonâ€), all from Proto-Turkic *Åpur, possibly from Proto-Turkic *Åp- (â€œto swallow, gulp downâ€).[1] Vasmer finds this phonetically doubtful.[2]
A Slavic construction, from *u- +â€ *pyÅ™ÑŒ, â€œflyerâ€ with a privative prefix. Compare *netopyÅ™ÑŒ. According to this hypothesis *Ç«pyrÑŒ could have originated as a taboo for *vÑŒlkolakÑŠ (cf. vukodlak).

The word would then indicate an uncremated corpse. He also lists alternative suggestions that others had proposed: a possible connection with *pyÅ™ÑŒ (â€œflyerâ€), as above; or from *vÑŠ- +â€ *pÄ›rÑŒ as a coinage related to vrÄ›piti (â€œto clingâ€), supposedly because a vampire bites and clings to its victims.

etm_info:
From Proto-Balto-Slavic *kweistei. Related to Latvian kvitÃªt (â€œto shimmer, to glimmerâ€).

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *á¸±weyt-, where Proto-Indo-European *á¸±w- is depalatalized to *kw- in Balto-Slavic before a back vowel but has its regular reflex Å›w- before a front vowel, and the complex pattern of related Proto-Slavic words with *kv- and *sv- (see Related terms, below) is due to analogical changes in both directions.
Per Rix (LIV), there are two separate roots, Proto-Indo-European *á¸±weyt- (â€œto become brightâ€) and Proto-Indo-European *kweyt- (â€œto shineâ€), the latter found only in Balto-Slavic.
Chernykh refers to a substitution of "West-European" *k in place of *á¸±-, presumably suggesting a borrowing from a Centum language to the West of Proto-Balto-Slavic.
Trubachev's theory is of "secondary centumization", which appears to be essentially the same as Chernykh's.

Per Derksen, from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°rob-Ã©ye-ti, from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°reb-; meanings "to rake" in daughter languages from confusion with the root *gÊ°rebÊ°- (see Proto-Slavic *gretÃ¬ (â€œto dig, to rake, to scrapeâ€)). Baltic cognates include Lithuanian grÃ³bti (â€œto seizeâ€), Latvian grÃ¢bt (â€œto seizeâ€). Indo-European cognates include Old Norse grÃ¡pa (â€œto seizeâ€). The same confusion appears to have happened elsewhere; compare Sanskrit à¤—à¥ƒà¤¹à¥à¤£à¤¾à¤¤à¤¿ (gá¹›há¹‡ÄÌti), à¤—à¥ƒà¤­à¥à¤£à¤¾à¤¤à¤¿ (gá¹›bhá¹‡ÄÌti, â€œto seize, to hold, to takeâ€). Avestan: grab- â€˜to grab, seize, takeâ€™, Old Persian: grab- â€˜to seize (as possesion), Persian Ú¯Ø±ÙØªÙ†â€ (gereftan), Ù¾Ø°ÛŒØ±ÙØªÙ†â€ (paziroftan).[1] English grab vs. Gothic ğŒ²ğ‚ğŒ°ğŒ±ğŒ°ğŒ½ (graban, â€œto digâ€), all of which come from *gÊ°rebÊ°-. Derksen does not derive this verb from *gÊ°rebÊ°- due to Winter's law, which is required to produce the acute *-a- of the Slavic root but would not operate in *gÊ°rebÊ°-.
Per Vasmer, Chernykh and Trubachev, this verb in fact derives from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°rob-Ã©ye-ti, from *gÊ°reb-; see also Proto-Slavic *gretÃ¬. Chernykh describes it as the causative of *gretÃ¬.
Per Rix (LIV), probably from Proto-Indo-European *gÊ°robhâ‚‚-Ã©ye-ti, from *gÊ°rebhâ‚‚-, which allows for Winter's law and also accounts for the Sanskrit -(b)h- (but still doesn't account for the Germanic forms, which are supposed to derive from a different root *gÊ°rebÊ°-).

etm_info:
Generally agreed to derive from Old High German Karl, name of the Frankish ruler Charlemagne (742-814) who ruled the western areas of Slavdom, from Proto-Germanic *karilaz (â€œfree manâ€).
Extended derivation:

Old High German Karl > Late Proto-Slavic *kÃµrÄ¾ÑŒ
The shift from hard o-stem to the soft jo-stem, as outlined in the chronology above, has several theories of origin:

Holzer explains the j-suffix as originating from a substantivized possessive adjective
Schenker suggests analogical replacement after agent nouns ending in *-teÄ¾ÑŒ or other words denoting leaders such as *cÄ›saÅ™ÑŒ and *kÑŠnÄ™dzÑŒ
Pronk-Tiethoff suggests the final *-Ä¾ÑŒ is due to the fact that Proto-Slavs likely perceived the Old High German final consonant as soft, similarly as in the loanword *grÄ™deÄ¾ÑŒ.
The word has been described as "without doubt the most famous Germanic loanword in Slavic" (Pronk-Tiethoff 2013) due to the fact that it's the only loanword in Slavic that can actually be dated, thus giving clues to the absolute dating of Proto-Slavic phonological developments. The fact that it regularly underwent historical Proto-Slavic sound laws, and that it's reflected in all three branches, is one of the chief indications to date Late Proto-Slavic (Common Slavic) to the ninth century.
However, this is comparatively late (only a century before Old Church Slavonic manuscripts were written), so other etymologies have been suggested:

Holzer derives it from the name of the Frankish ruler Charles Martel (688-741). The issue with this theory is that Charles Martel was not particularly important to the contemporary Slavs.
Stender-Petersen derives it from Proto-Germanic *kar(i)laz (â€œfree manâ€) (Old High German karl (â€œmanâ€)) with a semantic shift explained as "very ordinary".
These theories are generally thought of as less convincing than from Karl "Charlemagne", who was an actual king of (some) Slavs.

etm_info:
Of Germanic origin, with two proposed sources of borrowing:

For meaning beech: From Proto-West Germanic *bÅku (â€œbeechâ€)[1][2], formally equivalent to *bukÑŠ (â€œbeechâ€) +â€ *-y.
For meaning books, writs: From Gothic ğŒ±ğ‰ğŒºğ‰ğƒÂ pl (bÅkÅs, â€œbooksâ€) (per Vasmer, Trubachev).
The intrinsic relation between the two meanings is sometimes disputed (e.g. by Kluge), since there is no survived evidence for beech-based writing among early Germanic and Balto-Slavic people. It is possible (as noted by Mallory and Adams) that beech had religious significance for ancient Indo-European people and so was used to inscribe sacred symbols onto[2]. In this case, the extended meaning writ, sign would be directly borrowed from Germanic. A third hypothesis speculates that beechmast was used for counting and bookkeeping, whence the word innately developed a sense of â€œunit of data representationâ€ â†’ grapheme, writ.
